Note:
x86_64 Calling Convention Implementation

Implements both the System V AMD64 ABI (used on Linux, macOS, BSD, and other Unix systems)
and the Win64 ABI (used on Windows) calling conventions for x86_64 code generation.

This file performs the following tasks:
- Defines calling convention data structures for argument passing and register usage
- Creates System V AMD64 ABI and Win64 ABI convention instances with correct register maps
- Classifies function arguments as INTEGER or SSE class per ABI rules
- Maps argument indices to physical registers or stack positions
- Computes stack space requirements for spilled arguments
- Provides callee-saved and caller-saved register lists per convention
- Computes stack frame adjustments ensuring 16-byte alignment

This file is essential because of the following reasons:
- Correct calling convention handling is required for interoperability with C libraries and OS APIs
- System V and Win64 ABIs differ significantly in register usage, stack layout, and shadow space
- Proper frame alignment prevents segfaults on SSE instructions that require 16-byte alignment
- The register classification drives register allocation decisions across the backend

Dependencies:
- Imports LIR types for physical register constants
- Imports LIR node types for type inspection
- Imports machine code interface for target architecture constants
- Imports layout for heap allocation of convention structures
- Imports list for register list management
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/lir/lir.runa" as LIR
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/lir/lir_nodes.runa" as LIRNodes
Import "compiler/backend/machine_code/common/machine_code_interface.runa" as MachineCode
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Argument Classification Constants
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
The System V AMD64 ABI classifies each 8-byte unit of an argument into one of several
classes. INTEGER class arguments are passed in general-purpose registers, SSE class
arguments are passed in XMM registers, MEMORY class arguments are passed on the stack,
and NO_CLASS is used for padding or empty slots.

For Runa's current type system, all non-float types (Integer, Boolean, String pointers,
struct pointers, etc.) classify as INTEGER, and Float/Float64 classify as SSE. The
MEMORY class is used when register slots are exhausted.
@End Reasoning

Constant ARG_CLASS_INTEGER as Integer is 0     Note: Passed in GPR (Integer, Boolean, String, pointer, struct pointer)
Constant ARG_CLASS_SSE as Integer is 1         Note: Passed in XMM register (Float, Float64)
Constant ARG_CLASS_MEMORY as Integer is 2      Note: Passed on the stack (register slots exhausted or large struct)
Constant ARG_CLASS_NO_CLASS as Integer is 3    Note: Ignored or padding (zero-size types, void)

Note: Calling Convention Identifiers
Constant CALLING_CONV_SYSTEMV as Integer is 0  Note: System V AMD64 ABI (Linux, macOS, FreeBSD, OpenBSD, NetBSD)
Constant CALLING_CONV_WIN64 as Integer is 1    Note: Microsoft x64 calling convention (Windows)

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CallingConventionInfo Type Definition
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
CallingConventionInfo encapsulates all data needed to generate correct function prologues,
epilogues, call sequences, and register allocation constraints for a specific calling
convention.

The int_arg_registers and float_arg_registers fields point to Lists of physical register
IDs in argument-passing order. The callee_saved_registers and caller_saved_registers
fields point to Lists used by the register allocator to determine which registers must
be preserved across calls.

Structure layout (12 fields, 96 bytes):
  offset  0: convention_id          - CALLING_CONV_SYSTEMV or CALLING_CONV_WIN64
  offset  8: int_arg_registers      - List pointer: GPRs used for integer arguments in order
  offset 16: float_arg_registers    - List pointer: XMM regs used for float arguments in order
  offset 24: int_arg_count          - Number of GPRs available for integer arguments
  offset 32: float_arg_count        - Number of XMM regs available for float arguments
  offset 40: return_register        - GPR for integer return value (RAX)
  offset 48: float_return_register  - XMM for float return value (XMM0)
  offset 56: callee_saved_registers - List pointer: registers the callee must preserve
  offset 64: caller_saved_registers - List pointer: registers the caller must save before calls
  offset 72: stack_alignment        - Required stack alignment in bytes (16 for both ABIs)
  offset 80: red_zone_size          - Red zone below RSP (128 for System V, 0 for Win64)
  offset 88: shadow_space_size      - Shadow/home space in bytes (0 for System V, 32 for Win64)
@End Reasoning

Type called "CallingConventionInfo":
    convention_id as Integer           Note: CALLING_CONV_SYSTEMV or CALLING_CONV_WIN64
    int_arg_registers as Integer       Note: List of GPR register IDs for integer args
    float_arg_registers as Integer     Note: List of XMM register IDs for float args
    int_arg_count as Integer           Note: Number of integer argument registers
    float_arg_count as Integer         Note: Number of float argument registers
    return_register as Integer         Note: Integer return register ID (RAX = 0)
    float_return_register as Integer   Note: Float return register ID (XMM0 = 16)
    callee_saved_registers as Integer  Note: List of callee-saved register IDs
    caller_saved_registers as Integer  Note: List of caller-saved register IDs
    stack_alignment as Integer         Note: Stack alignment requirement in bytes
    red_zone_size as Integer           Note: Red zone size in bytes below RSP
    shadow_space_size as Integer       Note: Shadow/home space size in bytes
End Type

Note: Size: 12 fields * 8 bytes = 96 bytes per CallingConventionInfo

Note: ============================================================================
Note: System V AMD64 ABI Convention
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
The System V AMD64 ABI is used on all Unix-like systems (Linux, macOS, FreeBSD, etc.).
It is the primary calling convention for Runa since Linux is the primary target.

Key characteristics:
- 6 integer argument registers: RDI, RSI, RDX, RCX, R8, R9
- 8 float argument registers: XMM0 through XMM7
- Integer and float argument counts are tracked independently (each gets its own index)
- Return values in RAX (integer) or XMM0 (float)
- 128-byte red zone below RSP that leaf functions can use without adjusting RSP
- No shadow space requirement
- 16-byte stack alignment at the point of CALL instruction
- Callee-saved (nonvolatile): RBX, RBP, R12, R13, R14, R15
- Caller-saved (volatile): RAX, RCX, RDX, RSI, RDI, R8, R9, R10, R11, XMM0-XMM15
@End Reasoning

Process called "create_systemv_convention" returns Integer:
    Note: Allocate CallingConventionInfo structure (96 bytes)
    Let info be proc allocate from Layout with 96
    If info is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Set convention identifier
    __store(info, 0, CALLING_CONV_SYSTEMV)

    Note: Build integer argument register list: RDI(5), RSI(4), RDX(3), RCX(2), R8(8), R9(9)
    Let int_regs be proc list_create from List with 8
    If int_regs is 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc list_append from List with int_regs, 5 Note: RDI minus 1st integer arg
    proc list_append from List with int_regs, 4 Note: RSI minus 2nd integer arg
    proc list_append from List with int_regs, 3 Note: RDX minus 3rd integer arg
    proc list_append from List with int_regs, 2 Note: RCX minus 4th integer arg
    proc list_append from List with int_regs, 8 Note: R8  minus 5th integer arg
    proc list_append from List with int_regs, 9 Note: R9  minus 6th integer arg
    __store(info, 8, int_regs)

    Note: Build float argument register list: XMM0(16) through XMM7(23)
    Let float_regs be proc list_create from List with 8
    If float_regs is 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc list_append from List with float_regs, 16 Note: XMM0 minus 1st float arg
    proc list_append from List with float_regs, 17 Note: XMM1 minus 2nd float arg
    proc list_append from List with float_regs, 18 Note: XMM2 minus 3rd float arg
    proc list_append from List with float_regs, 19 Note: XMM3 minus 4th float arg
    proc list_append from List with float_regs, 20 Note: XMM4 minus 5th float arg
    proc list_append from List with float_regs, 21 Note: XMM5 minus 6th float arg
    proc list_append from List with float_regs, 22 Note: XMM6 minus 7th float arg
    proc list_append from List with float_regs, 23 Note: XMM7 minus 8th float arg
    __store(info, 16, float_regs)

    Note: Set argument register counts
    __store(info, 24, 6)   Note: 6 integer argument registers
    __store(info, 32, 8)   Note: 8 float argument registers

    Note: Set return registers
    __store(info, 40, 0)   Note: RAX(0) for integer returns
    __store(info, 48, 16)  Note: XMM0(16) for float returns

    Note: Build callee-saved register list: RBX(1), RBP(6), R12(12), R13(13), R14(14), R15(15)
    Let callee_saved be proc list_create from List with 8
    If callee_saved is 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc list_append from List with callee_saved, 1 Note: RBX
    proc list_append from List with callee_saved, 6 Note: RBP
    proc list_append from List with callee_saved, 12 Note: R12
    proc list_append from List with callee_saved, 13 Note: R13
    proc list_append from List with callee_saved, 14 Note: R14
    proc list_append from List with callee_saved, 15 Note: R15
    __store(info, 56, callee_saved)

    Note: Build caller-saved register list: RAX(0), RCX(2), RDX(3), RSI(4), RDI(5),
    Note: R8(8), R9(9), R10(10), R11(11)
    Note: XMM0-XMM15 are also caller-saved but tracked separately for register allocation
    Let caller_saved be proc list_create from List with 16
    If caller_saved is 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc list_append from List with caller_saved, 0 Note: RAX
    proc list_append from List with caller_saved, 2 Note: RCX
    proc list_append from List with caller_saved, 3 Note: RDX
    proc list_append from List with caller_saved, 4 Note: RSI
    proc list_append from List with caller_saved, 5 Note: RDI
    proc list_append from List with caller_saved, 8 Note: R8
    proc list_append from List with caller_saved, 9 Note: R9
    proc list_append from List with caller_saved, 10 Note: R10
    proc list_append from List with caller_saved, 11 Note: R11
    __store(info, 64, caller_saved)

    Note: Set stack parameters
    __store(info, 72, 16)   Note: 16-byte stack alignment
    __store(info, 80, 128)  Note: 128-byte red zone
    __store(info, 88, 0)    Note: No shadow space in System V

    Return info
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Win64 ABI Convention
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
The Win64 ABI (Microsoft x64 calling convention) is used on Windows systems. It differs
significantly from System V:

Key characteristics:
- 4 integer argument registers: RCX, RDX, R8, R9
- 4 float argument registers: XMM0, XMM1, XMM2, XMM3
- Integer and float arguments share positional slots (arg 1 uses either RCX or XMM0,
  never both; arg 2 uses either RDX or XMM1, etc.)
- Return values in RAX (integer) or XMM0 (float)
- No red zone
- 32-byte shadow space (home space) that the caller must allocate for the callee to
  spill the 4 register arguments, even if the callee has fewer than 4 parameters
- 16-byte stack alignment at the point of CALL instruction
- Callee-saved (nonvolatile): RBX, RBP, RDI, RSI, R12, R13, R14, R15, XMM6-XMM15
  Note: RDI and RSI are callee-saved in Win64 but caller-saved in System V
- Caller-saved (volatile): RAX, RCX, RDX, R8, R9, R10, R11, XMM0-XMM5
@End Reasoning

Process called "create_win64_convention" returns Integer:
    Note: Allocate CallingConventionInfo structure (96 bytes)
    Let info be proc allocate from Layout with 96
    If info is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Set convention identifier
    __store(info, 0, CALLING_CONV_WIN64)

    Note: Build integer argument register list: RCX(2), RDX(3), R8(8), R9(9)
    Let int_regs be proc list_create from List with 4
    If int_regs is 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc list_append from List with int_regs, 2 Note: RCX minus 1st integer arg
    proc list_append from List with int_regs, 3 Note: RDX minus 2nd integer arg
    proc list_append from List with int_regs, 8 Note: R8  minus 3rd integer arg
    proc list_append from List with int_regs, 9 Note: R9  minus 4th integer arg
    __store(info, 8, int_regs)

    Note: Build float argument register list: XMM0(16), XMM1(17), XMM2(18), XMM3(19)
    Let float_regs be proc list_create from List with 4
    If float_regs is 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc list_append from List with float_regs, 16 Note: XMM0 minus 1st float arg
    proc list_append from List with float_regs, 17 Note: XMM1 minus 2nd float arg
    proc list_append from List with float_regs, 18 Note: XMM2 minus 3rd float arg
    proc list_append from List with float_regs, 19 Note: XMM3 minus 4th float arg
    __store(info, 16, float_regs)

    Note: Set argument register counts
    __store(info, 24, 4)   Note: 4 integer argument registers
    __store(info, 32, 4)   Note: 4 float argument registers

    Note: Set return registers
    __store(info, 40, 0)   Note: RAX(0) for integer returns
    __store(info, 48, 16)  Note: XMM0(16) for float returns

    Note: Build callee-saved register list: RBX(1), RBP(6), RDI(5), RSI(4),
    Note: R12(12), R13(13), R14(14), R15(15)
    Note: XMM6-XMM15 are also callee-saved on Win64 (added to list for register allocator)
    Let callee_saved be proc list_create from List with 20
    If callee_saved is 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc list_append from List with callee_saved, 1 Note: RBX
    proc list_append from List with callee_saved, 6 Note: RBP
    proc list_append from List with callee_saved, 5 Note: RDI (callee-saved on Win64, unlike System V)
    proc list_append from List with callee_saved, 4 Note: RSI (callee-saved on Win64, unlike System V)
    proc list_append from List with callee_saved, 12 Note: R12
    proc list_append from List with callee_saved, 13 Note: R13
    proc list_append from List with callee_saved, 14 Note: R14
    proc list_append from List with callee_saved, 15 Note: R15
    proc list_append from List with callee_saved, 22 Note: XMM6
    proc list_append from List with callee_saved, 23 Note: XMM7
    proc list_append from List with callee_saved, 24 Note: XMM8
    proc list_append from List with callee_saved, 25 Note: XMM9
    proc list_append from List with callee_saved, 26 Note: XMM10
    proc list_append from List with callee_saved, 27 Note: XMM11
    proc list_append from List with callee_saved, 28 Note: XMM12
    proc list_append from List with callee_saved, 29 Note: XMM13
    proc list_append from List with callee_saved, 30 Note: XMM14
    proc list_append from List with callee_saved, 31 Note: XMM15
    __store(info, 56, callee_saved)

    Note: Build caller-saved register list: RAX(0), RCX(2), RDX(3), R8(8), R9(9),
    Note: R10(10), R11(11), XMM0(16)-XMM5(21)
    Let caller_saved be proc list_create from List with 16
    If caller_saved is 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc list_append from List with caller_saved, 0 Note: RAX
    proc list_append from List with caller_saved, 2 Note: RCX
    proc list_append from List with caller_saved, 3 Note: RDX
    proc list_append from List with caller_saved, 8 Note: R8
    proc list_append from List with caller_saved, 9 Note: R9
    proc list_append from List with caller_saved, 10 Note: R10
    proc list_append from List with caller_saved, 11 Note: R11
    proc list_append from List with caller_saved, 16 Note: XMM0
    proc list_append from List with caller_saved, 17 Note: XMM1
    proc list_append from List with caller_saved, 18 Note: XMM2
    proc list_append from List with caller_saved, 19 Note: XMM3
    proc list_append from List with caller_saved, 20 Note: XMM4
    proc list_append from List with caller_saved, 21 Note: XMM5
    __store(info, 64, caller_saved)

    Note: Set stack parameters
    __store(info, 72, 16)   Note: 16-byte stack alignment
    __store(info, 80, 0)    Note: No red zone on Win64
    __store(info, 88, 32)   Note: 32-byte shadow space (home area)

    Return info
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Argument Classification
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Classifies a function argument based on its HIR type information to determine whether
it should be passed in a general-purpose register (INTEGER class) or an XMM register
(SSE class).

The classification follows the type_kind encoding used throughout the compiler:
  type_kind 1 = Integer  -> ARG_CLASS_INTEGER
  type_kind 2 = Float    -> ARG_CLASS_SSE
  type_kind 3 = String   -> ARG_CLASS_INTEGER (String is a pointer, passed in GPR)
  type_kind 4 = Boolean  -> ARG_CLASS_INTEGER
  type_kind 0 = Void     -> ARG_CLASS_NO_CLASS

All pointer types, struct pointers, array pointers, and reference types are passed as
INTEGER class because they are 8-byte pointer values on x86-64.

The convention parameter is accepted for future extensibility (Win64 has different
struct-passing rules for aggregates > 8 bytes) but currently both ABIs use the same
classification logic for Runa's types since all non-scalar aggregates are heap-allocated
and passed by pointer.
@End Reasoning

Process called "classify_argument" that takes arg_type as Integer, convention as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: If arg_type is equal to 0 (0), treat as void/no-class
    If arg_type is 0:
        Return ARG_CLASS_NO_CLASS
    End If

    Note: Read the type_kind from the type info structure
    Note: type_kind is stored at offset 0 of the type info (8 bytes)
    Let type_kind be __load(arg_type, 0)

    Note: Type kind 0: Void - no argument class
    If type_kind is 0:
        Return ARG_CLASS_NO_CLASS
    End If

    Note: Type kind 2: Float/Float64 - passed in XMM registers
    If type_kind is 2:
        Return ARG_CLASS_SSE
    End If

    Note: Type kind 1: Integer - passed in GPR
    If type_kind is 1:
        Return ARG_CLASS_INTEGER
    End If

    Note: Type kind 3: String - passed as pointer in GPR
    If type_kind is 3:
        Return ARG_CLASS_INTEGER
    End If

    Note: Type kind 4: Boolean - passed in GPR (zero-extended to 64 bits)
    If type_kind is 4:
        Return ARG_CLASS_INTEGER
    End If

    Note: All other types (struct pointers, array pointers, reference types,
    Note: optional types, union types, function pointers, etc.) are 8-byte
    Note: pointer values on x86-64 and are passed in general-purpose registers
    Return ARG_CLASS_INTEGER
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Argument Register Mapping
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Maps a function argument (identified by its position within its class) to the physical
register that should hold it, according to the specified calling convention.

For System V AMD64 ABI:
  INTEGER class: arg 0->RDI(5), 1->RSI(4), 2->RDX(3), 3->RCX(2), 4->R8(8), 5->R9(9)
  SSE class:     arg 0->XMM0(16), 1->XMM1(17), ..., 7->XMM7(23)

For Win64 ABI:
  INTEGER class: arg 0->RCX(2), 1->RDX(3), 2->R8(8), 3->R9(9)
  SSE class:     arg 0->XMM0(16), 1->XMM1(17), 2->XMM2(18), 3->XMM3(19)

Note on Win64 positional slots: In Win64, integer and float arguments share positional
slots. This means if argument 0 is an integer (in RCX), argument 1 is a float (in XMM1,
NOT XMM0). The arg_index passed here must already account for this positional sharing.
The caller is responsible for tracking the combined positional index for Win64.

Returns the physical register ID, or -1 if the argument must be passed on the stack
because all register slots for that class are exhausted.
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_arg_register" that takes convention as Integer, arg_index as Integer, arg_class as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Validate arg_index is non-negative
    If arg_index is less than 0:
        Return -1
    End If

    Note: NO_CLASS arguments do not occupy a register
    If arg_class is ARG_CLASS_NO_CLASS:
        Return -1
    End If

    Note: MEMORY class arguments are explicitly on the stack
    If arg_class is ARG_CLASS_MEMORY:
        Return -1
    End If

    Note: System V AMD64 ABI
    If convention is CALLING_CONV_SYSTEMV:
        If arg_class is ARG_CLASS_INTEGER:
            Note: 6 integer argument registers in System V
            If arg_index is 0:
                Return 5   Note: RDI
            End If
            If arg_index is 1:
                Return 4   Note: RSI
            End If
            If arg_index is 2:
                Return 3   Note: RDX
            End If
            If arg_index is 3:
                Return 2   Note: RCX
            End If
            If arg_index is 4:
                Return 8   Note: R8
            End If
            If arg_index is 5:
                Return 9   Note: R9
            End If
            Note: arg_index >= 6: passed on stack
            Return -1
        End If

        If arg_class is ARG_CLASS_SSE:
            Note: 8 float argument registers in System V: XMM0 through XMM7
            If arg_index is less than 8:
                Return 16 plus arg_index  Note: XMM0(16) plus offset
            End If
            Note: arg_index >= 8: passed on stack
            Return -1
        End If

        Note: Unrecognized class falls to stack
        Return -1
    End If

    Note: Win64 ABI
    If convention is CALLING_CONV_WIN64:
        If arg_class is ARG_CLASS_INTEGER:
            Note: 4 integer argument registers in Win64
            If arg_index is 0:
                Return 2   Note: RCX
            End If
            If arg_index is 1:
                Return 3   Note: RDX
            End If
            If arg_index is 2:
                Return 8   Note: R8
            End If
            If arg_index is 3:
                Return 9   Note: R9
            End If
            Note: arg_index >= 4: passed on stack
            Return -1
        End If

        If arg_class is ARG_CLASS_SSE:
            Note: 4 float argument registers in Win64: XMM0 through XMM3
            If arg_index is 0:
                Return 16  Note: XMM0
            End If
            If arg_index is 1:
                Return 17  Note: XMM1
            End If
            If arg_index is 2:
                Return 18  Note: XMM2
            End If
            If arg_index is 3:
                Return 19  Note: XMM3
            End If
            Note: arg_index >= 4: passed on stack
            Return -1
        End If

        Note: Unrecognized class falls to stack
        Return -1
    End If

    Note: Unknown convention: all arguments on stack
    Return -1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Stack Argument Space Computation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Computes the total stack space (in bytes) required for function arguments that do not
fit into registers. Each stack argument occupies 8 bytes (one quadword slot) on x86-64,
regardless of its actual size (values smaller than 8 bytes are zero-extended or
sign-extended to fill the slot).

For System V AMD64 ABI:
  - Integer arguments beyond the 6th go on the stack
  - Float arguments beyond the 8th go on the stack
  - Integer and float argument positions are tracked independently

For Win64 ABI:
  - Arguments share positional slots (arg position is shared between int and float)
  - Arguments beyond the 4th position go on the stack
  - Additionally, 32 bytes of shadow space is always reserved (handled separately in
    frame computation, not counted here)

The arg_types parameter is a pointer to an array of type info pointers, and arg_count
is the total number of arguments.
@End Reasoning

Process called "compute_stack_args_size" that takes convention as Integer, arg_types as Integer, arg_count as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: If no arguments, no stack space needed
    If arg_count is 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If arg_types is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let stack_bytes be 0

    If convention is CALLING_CONV_SYSTEMV:
        Note: System V: integer and float argument indices are independent
        Let int_index be 0
        Let float_index be 0

        Let i be 0
        While i is less than arg_count:
            Note: Read the type info pointer for this argument
            Let type_ptr be __load(arg_types, i multiplied by 8)
            Let arg_class be classify_argument(type_ptr, convention)

            If arg_class is ARG_CLASS_INTEGER:
                If int_index is greater than or equal to 6:
                    Note: This integer argument spills to the stack
                    Set stack_bytes to stack_bytes plus 8
                End If
                Set int_index to int_index plus 1
            End If

            If arg_class is ARG_CLASS_SSE:
                If float_index is greater than or equal to 8:
                    Note: This float argument spills to the stack
                    Set stack_bytes to stack_bytes plus 8
                End If
                Set float_index to float_index plus 1
            End If

            If arg_class is ARG_CLASS_MEMORY:
                Note: Explicitly stack-passed arguments always take 8 bytes
                Set stack_bytes to stack_bytes plus 8
            End If

            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If

    If convention is CALLING_CONV_WIN64:
        Note: Win64: arguments share positional slots (1st arg is position 0, etc.)
        Note: The first 4 positional slots go in registers, rest on stack
        If arg_count is greater than 4:
            Let spill_count be arg_count minus 4
            Set stack_bytes to spill_count multiplied by 8
        End If
    End If

    Note: Ensure stack argument area is 16-byte aligned
    Note: Each argument is 8 bytes, so we align the total to 16
    Let remainder be stack_bytes modulo by 16
    If remainder is not 0:
        Set stack_bytes to stack_bytes plus (16 minus remainder)
    End If

    Return stack_bytes
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Callee-Saved Register List
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Returns a pointer to the List of callee-saved register IDs for the specified calling
convention. Callee-saved (nonvolatile) registers must be saved in the function prologue
and restored in the epilogue if the function uses them.

The returned list is freshly created each time to allow the caller to modify it without
affecting the canonical convention data. This is important because register allocation
may need to filter or reorder the list.

System V callee-saved GPRs: RBX(1), RBP(6), R12(12), R13(13), R14(14), R15(15)
Win64 callee-saved GPRs:    RBX(1), RBP(6), RDI(5), RSI(4), R12(12), R13(13), R14(14), R15(15)
Win64 callee-saved XMMs:    XMM6(22)-XMM15(31)
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_callee_saved_list" that takes convention as Integer returns Integer:
    Let result be proc list_create from List with 20
    If result is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If convention is CALLING_CONV_SYSTEMV:
        proc list_append from List with result, 1 Note: RBX
        proc list_append from List with result, 6 Note: RBP
        proc list_append from List with result, 12 Note: R12
        proc list_append from List with result, 13 Note: R13
        proc list_append from List with result, 14 Note: R14
        proc list_append from List with result, 15 Note: R15
        Return result
    End If

    If convention is CALLING_CONV_WIN64:
        Note: GPRs
        proc list_append from List with result, 1 Note: RBX
        proc list_append from List with result, 6 Note: RBP
        proc list_append from List with result, 5 Note: RDI
        proc list_append from List with result, 4 Note: RSI
        proc list_append from List with result, 12 Note: R12
        proc list_append from List with result, 13 Note: R13
        proc list_append from List with result, 14 Note: R14
        proc list_append from List with result, 15 Note: R15
        Note: XMM registers that are callee-saved on Win64
        proc list_append from List with result, 22 Note: XMM6
        proc list_append from List with result, 23 Note: XMM7
        proc list_append from List with result, 24 Note: XMM8
        proc list_append from List with result, 25 Note: XMM9
        proc list_append from List with result, 26 Note: XMM10
        proc list_append from List with result, 27 Note: XMM11
        proc list_append from List with result, 28 Note: XMM12
        proc list_append from List with result, 29 Note: XMM13
        proc list_append from List with result, 30 Note: XMM14
        proc list_append from List with result, 31 Note: XMM15
        Return result
    End If

    Note: Unknown convention: return empty list
    Return result
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Caller-Saved Register List
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Returns a pointer to the List of caller-saved register IDs for the specified calling
convention. Caller-saved (volatile) registers may be clobbered by any function call,
so the caller must save them before a call if their values are still needed afterward.

The returned list is freshly created each time to allow modification without affecting
canonical data.

System V caller-saved GPRs: RAX(0), RCX(2), RDX(3), RSI(4), RDI(5), R8(8), R9(9), R10(10), R11(11)
Win64 caller-saved GPRs:    RAX(0), RCX(2), RDX(3), R8(8), R9(9), R10(10), R11(11)
Win64 caller-saved XMMs:    XMM0(16)-XMM5(21)
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_caller_saved_list" that takes convention as Integer returns Integer:
    Let result be proc list_create from List with 16
    If result is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If convention is CALLING_CONV_SYSTEMV:
        proc list_append from List with result, 0 Note: RAX
        proc list_append from List with result, 2 Note: RCX
        proc list_append from List with result, 3 Note: RDX
        proc list_append from List with result, 4 Note: RSI
        proc list_append from List with result, 5 Note: RDI
        proc list_append from List with result, 8 Note: R8
        proc list_append from List with result, 9 Note: R9
        proc list_append from List with result, 10 Note: R10
        proc list_append from List with result, 11 Note: R11
        Return result
    End If

    If convention is CALLING_CONV_WIN64:
        Note: GPRs
        proc list_append from List with result, 0 Note: RAX
        proc list_append from List with result, 2 Note: RCX
        proc list_append from List with result, 3 Note: RDX
        proc list_append from List with result, 8 Note: R8
        proc list_append from List with result, 9 Note: R9
        proc list_append from List with result, 10 Note: R10
        proc list_append from List with result, 11 Note: R11
        Note: XMM registers that are caller-saved on Win64
        proc list_append from List with result, 16 Note: XMM0
        proc list_append from List with result, 17 Note: XMM1
        proc list_append from List with result, 18 Note: XMM2
        proc list_append from List with result, 19 Note: XMM3
        proc list_append from List with result, 20 Note: XMM4
        proc list_append from List with result, 21 Note: XMM5
        Return result
    End If

    Note: Unknown convention: return empty list
    Return result
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Stack Frame Adjustment Computation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Computes the total frame size ensuring the stack remains 16-byte aligned at the point
where the callee's code begins executing (after prologue push instructions).

The x86-64 ABI requires that the stack pointer (RSP) is 16-byte aligned immediately
before the CALL instruction. The CALL instruction pushes the 8-byte return address,
so upon function entry RSP is 8 bytes misaligned from 16.

The typical prologue is:
  push rbp         -> RSP -= 8 (now 16-byte aligned if no callee-saved pushes follow)
  mov rbp, rsp
  push callee-saved registers (each 8 bytes)
  sub rsp, local_size

The total adjustment below RBP must maintain 16-byte alignment. The formula accounts for:
1. The return address (8 bytes, already on stack from CALL)
2. The pushed RBP (8 bytes)
3. The callee-saved register pushes (callee_saved_count * 8 bytes)
4. The local variable space (local_size bytes)
5. Win64 shadow space (if applicable)

After accounting for (1) return address + (2) pushed RBP + (3) callee-saved pushes,
the remaining space to allocate (local_size + any padding) must result in RSP being
16-byte aligned.
@End Reasoning

Process called "compute_frame_adjustment" that takes convention as Integer, local_size as Integer, callee_saved_count as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: The CALL instruction pushed 8 bytes (return address)
    Note: push rbp adds another 8 bytes
    Note: Each callee-saved register push adds 8 bytes
    Note: Total bytes pushed before RSP adjustment: 8 (ret addr) + 8 (rbp) + callee_saved_count * 8
    Let pushed_bytes be 16 plus (callee_saved_count multiplied by 8)

    Note: Start with the requested local variable space
    Let frame_size be local_size

    Note: For Win64, add shadow space to the frame
    If convention is CALLING_CONV_WIN64:
        Set frame_size to frame_size plus 32
    End If

    Note: The total below the initial RSP (at function entry, before our prologue) is:
    Note:   pushed_bytes + frame_size
    Note: This total must be a multiple of 16 for alignment.
    Note: .
    Note: At function entry, RSP was 16-byte aligned - 8 (due to CALL pushing ret addr).
    Note: After push rbp: RSP is 16-byte aligned if callee_saved_count is even, or 8-misaligned if odd.
    Note: .
    Note: We need: (pushed_bytes + frame_size) % 16 == 0
    Note: Since pushed_bytes = 16 + callee_saved_count * 8:
    Note:   If callee_saved_count is even: pushed_bytes % 16 == 0, so frame_size must be % 16 == 0
    Note:   If callee_saved_count is odd:  pushed_bytes % 16 == 8, so frame_size must be % 16 == 8

    Let total be pushed_bytes plus frame_size
    Let remainder be total modulo by 16

    If remainder is not 0:
        Note: Add padding to achieve 16-byte alignment
        Set frame_size to frame_size plus (16 minus remainder)
    End If

    Return frame_size
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Callee-Saved Register Query
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Determines whether a given physical register is callee-saved in the specified calling
convention. Returns 1 if the register must be preserved by the callee (saved in
prologue, restored in epilogue), or 0 if it is caller-saved (volatile).

This is used by the register allocator to decide whether a register needs
save/restore code in the function prologue/epilogue, and by the call sequence
generator to determine which registers survive across call sites.

RSP(7) is technically preserved by the callee but is not listed as callee-saved
because it is managed by prologue/epilogue frame setup code, not by explicit
save/restore pairs. It is handled separately.
@End Reasoning

Process called "is_callee_saved" that takes convention as Integer, reg_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: RSP(7) is always preserved but handled separately by frame management
    If reg_id is 7:
        Return 0
    End If

    If convention is CALLING_CONV_SYSTEMV:
        Note: System V callee-saved GPRs: RBX(1), RBP(6), R12(12), R13(13), R14(14), R15(15)
        If reg_id is 1:
            Return 1  Note: RBX
        End If
        If reg_id is 6:
            Return 1  Note: RBP
        End If
        If reg_id is 12:
            Return 1  Note: R12
        End If
        If reg_id is 13:
            Return 1  Note: R13
        End If
        If reg_id is 14:
            Return 1  Note: R14
        End If
        If reg_id is 15:
            Return 1  Note: R15
        End If
        Note: All other registers (including all XMM regs) are caller-saved in System V
        Return 0
    End If

    If convention is CALLING_CONV_WIN64:
        Note: Win64 callee-saved GPRs: RBX(1), RBP(6), RDI(5), RSI(4), R12-R15
        If reg_id is 1:
            Return 1  Note: RBX
        End If
        If reg_id is 4:
            Return 1  Note: RSI (callee-saved on Win64)
        End If
        If reg_id is 5:
            Return 1  Note: RDI (callee-saved on Win64)
        End If
        If reg_id is 6:
            Return 1  Note: RBP
        End If
        If reg_id is 12:
            Return 1  Note: R12
        End If
        If reg_id is 13:
            Return 1  Note: R13
        End If
        If reg_id is 14:
            Return 1  Note: R14
        End If
        If reg_id is 15:
            Return 1  Note: R15
        End If
        Note: Win64 callee-saved XMMs: XMM6(22) through XMM15(31)
        If reg_id is greater than or equal to 22:
            If reg_id is less than or equal to 31:
                Return 1
            End If
        End If
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Unknown convention: assume nothing is callee-saved (safest default)
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Convention Selection Helper
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Selects the appropriate calling convention based on the target operating system.
Linux, macOS, FreeBSD, OpenBSD, and NetBSD use System V AMD64 ABI.
Windows uses Win64 ABI.
Bare metal and WASI default to System V since it is the more common convention
for standalone executables and WASI follows Unix conventions.

This function returns a freshly allocated CallingConventionInfo structure configured
for the selected convention. The caller owns the returned pointer.
@End Reasoning

Process called "create_convention_for_target" that takes target_os as Integer returns Integer:
    If target_os is MachineCode.TARGET_OS_WINDOWS:
        Return create_win64_convention()
    End If

    Note: All other operating systems use System V AMD64 ABI
    Return create_systemv_convention()
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Return Register Selection
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Returns the physical register ID for the function return value based on the type
classification and calling convention. Both System V and Win64 use RAX for integer
returns and XMM0 for float returns, but this function abstracts the convention for
consistency and future extensibility (e.g., 128-bit returns in RDX:RAX).
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_return_register" that takes convention as Integer, return_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Let arg_class be classify_argument(return_type, convention)

    If arg_class is ARG_CLASS_SSE:
        Return 16  Note: XMM0 for float returns
    End If

    Note: INTEGER, MEMORY, NO_CLASS all return via RAX (or void returns RAX conventionally)
    Return 0  Note: RAX for integer/pointer returns
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Win64 Shadow Space Query
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Returns the shadow space (home space) size in bytes for the given convention.
Win64 requires 32 bytes of shadow space to be allocated by the caller on the stack,
even for functions with fewer than 4 parameters. This space allows the callee to spill
the register arguments to known stack locations.

System V has no shadow space requirement.

This value must be added to the stack allocation before any CALL instruction on Win64.
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_shadow_space" that takes convention as Integer returns Integer:
    If convention is CALLING_CONV_WIN64:
        Return 32
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Red Zone Query
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Returns the red zone size in bytes for the given convention.
System V AMD64 ABI provides a 128-byte red zone below RSP that leaf functions may use
for temporary storage without adjusting RSP. This optimization avoids the cost of
sub/add RSP in small leaf functions.

Win64 has no red zone.

Leaf functions (functions that make no calls) can use the red zone to avoid stack frame
setup entirely. Non-leaf functions must not use the red zone because called functions
would overwrite it.
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_red_zone_size" that takes convention as Integer returns Integer:
    If convention is CALLING_CONV_SYSTEMV:
        Return 128
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Maximum Register Argument Count
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Returns the maximum number of arguments that can be passed in registers for a given
argument class and convention. This is used by the register allocator and call
sequence generator to determine when arguments spill to the stack.
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_max_reg_args" that takes convention as Integer, arg_class as Integer returns Integer:
    If convention is CALLING_CONV_SYSTEMV:
        If arg_class is ARG_CLASS_INTEGER:
            Return 6   Note: RDI, RSI, RDX, RCX, R8, R9
        End If
        If arg_class is ARG_CLASS_SSE:
            Return 8   Note: XMM0 through XMM7
        End If
        Return 0
    End If

    If convention is CALLING_CONV_WIN64:
        If arg_class is ARG_CLASS_INTEGER:
            Return 4   Note: RCX, RDX, R8, R9
        End If
        If arg_class is ARG_CLASS_SSE:
            Return 4   Note: XMM0 through XMM3
        End If
        Return 0
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Stack Argument Offset Computation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Computes the stack offset (relative to RSP at the point of the CALL instruction) for
an argument that must be passed on the stack.

For System V AMD64 ABI:
  Stack arguments are at [RSP + 0], [RSP + 8], [RSP + 16], etc. (from the caller's
  perspective before the CALL). After the CALL pushes the return address, these become
  [RSP + 8], [RSP + 16], [RSP + 24] from the callee's perspective.

For Win64 ABI:
  The first 4 argument positions always have shadow space at [RSP + 0] through
  [RSP + 24] (from the caller's perspective). Stack arguments for positions > or equal to 4
  start at [RSP + 32]. After the CALL, callee sees them at [RSP + 40], etc.

The stack_arg_index parameter is the zero-based index among stack-passed arguments
(not the overall argument index). For example, if 3 args are in registers and the
4th is on the stack, stack_arg_index for the 4th argument is 0.
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_stack_arg_offset" that takes convention as Integer, stack_arg_index as Integer returns Integer:
    If stack_arg_index is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If convention is CALLING_CONV_SYSTEMV:
        Note: Stack args start immediately at RSP (caller's view)
        Return stack_arg_index multiplied by 8
    End If

    If convention is CALLING_CONV_WIN64:
        Note: First 32 bytes are shadow space, stack args follow
        Return 32 plus (stack_arg_index multiplied by 8)
    End If

    Return stack_arg_index multiplied by 8
End Process
